*What is the relationship between the components of the weather and their impact on each other?* By Ng Ye Kai

Questions to answer: What is the impact of the monsoon/other seasons on monthly humidity and temperature? What is the impact of the monsoon/other seasons on wet bulb temperature what is the impact of higher average monthly temperatures on wet bulb temperature? what is the relationship between relative humidity and wet bulb temperature? Considering: Air quality records (PM2.5) + relationship with rainfall/humidity Rainfall - temperature - humidity relationship WBGT display over the years rainfall over the years Air quality over the years

Resources: Wet Bulb Temperature - Hourly; https://beta.data.gov.sg/datasets/d_f222c70a7c00c5a5a9d4ec432d67f6e8/view Recorded by placing a piece of wet cloth over a temperature recorder and measuring temperature after

Relative Humidity - Monthly Mean; https://beta.data.gov.sg/datasets/d_e3b1111a26b2aefef4f386c068d4ca5d/view Recorded by calculating the difference between WBT and normal temperature

Surface Air Temperature - Monthly Mean; https://beta.data.gov.sg/datasets/d_755290a24afe70c8f9e8bcbf9f251573/view Recorded by a temperature recorder not under direct sunlight, taking the monthly mean of temperatures

Rainfall - Monthly Total; https://beta.data.gov.sg/datasets/d_b16d06b83473fdfcc92ed9d37b66ba58/view Recorded by collecting rainfall level at the station and adding each day into a month

Historical PSI - 24-hr; https://beta.data.gov.sg/datasets/d_b4cf557f8750260d229c49fd768e11ed/view - ERROR in formatting at record for 4/4/2016 00:00, had to manually reformat. Record of historical PSI levels

Historical PM 2.5 - 1-hr; https://beta.data.gov.sg/datasets/d_6c0d5fc34838b12472475fdb73c0af29/view - ERROR in formatting at record for 4/4/2016 00:00, had to manually reformat. Record of historical PM 2.5 levels in the

Surface Air Temperature - Monthly Mean Daily Minimum; https://beta.data.gov.sg/datasets/d_c92edf841336f03ab51c6693ac8d33ad/view Temperature mean daily min by month

Surface Air Temperature - Monthly Mean Daily Maximum; https://beta.data.gov.sg/datasets/d_b0fb69de67054d6d741bea78274ecc2a/view Temperature mean daily max by month

# Data Processing
# Import modules
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from datetime import datetime, timedelta


# Functions for turning date formats to timestamps
date_format = '%d/%m/%Y %H:%M'
def convert_to_timestamp(value):
    # Attempt to parse and convert to timestamp
    date_object = datetime.strptime(value, date_format)
    return int(date_object.timestamp())

date_format1 = '%Y-%m'
def convert_to_timestamp1(value):
    # Attempt to parse and convert to timestamp
    date_object = datetime.strptime(value, date_format1)
    return int(date_object.timestamp())

date_format2 = '%Y-%m-%d/%H'
def convert_to_timestamp2(value,value1):
    # Attempt to parse and convert to timestamp
    if value1 == '24':
        # If hour is 24, set hour to 0 and add one day to the date part
        date_object = datetime.strptime(value, '%Y-%m-%d') + timedelta(days=1)
    else:
        timestamp = value + '/' + value1
        date_object = datetime.strptime(timestamp, date_format2)
    return int(date_object.timestamp())

date_format3 = '%Y'
def convert_to_timestamp3(value):
    # Attempt to parse and convert to timestamp
    date_object = datetime.strptime(value, date_format3)
    return int(date_object.timestamp())



# Get and read file data
file = 'datasets/Historical1hrPM2.5.csv'
data = np.genfromtxt(file,delimiter=',',dtype=['U50','i8','i8','i8','i8','i8'],names=True)
# could also use specific cols like:
# data = np.genfromtxt(file,delimiter=',',dtype=['U50','i8'],usecols=(0,1),names=True)

# Iterate through the array and update date strings to timestamps
for i in range(len(data)):
    temp = list(data[i])
    temp[0] = convert_to_timestamp(temp[0])
    data[i] = tuple(temp)
# Changing array data types
data = np.array(data,dtype=[('timestamp','<i8'), ('north', 'i4'), ('south', 'i4'), ('east', 'i4'), ('west', 'i4'), ('central', 'i4')])

# Convert Unix timestamps to datetime objects
timestamps = np.array([datetime.fromtimestamp(ts) for ts in data['timestamp']])
# Extract the year from each datetime object
years = np.array([ts.year for ts in timestamps])
# Group the values by year and calculate the average, as well as convert the year back to timestamp
unique_years = np.unique(years)
average_values = np.array([np.mean(((data['north']+data['south']+data['east']+data['west']+data['central'])/5)[years == year]) for year in unique_years])
for i in range(len(unique_years)):
    unique_years[i] = convert_to_timestamp3(str(unique_years[i]))

# Plot table and adjust x value representation
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.grid(True)
xlabels = ('2014', '2016', '2018','2020', '2022','2024')
xticks = [1388509200,1451581200,1514739600,1577811600,1640970000,1704042000]
plt.plot(data['timestamp'],(data['north']+data['south']+data['east']+data['west']+data['central'])/5, label='Raw Data', linewidth=0.2)
plt.plot(unique_years, average_values, marker='o', linestyle='-', label='Average Yearly Total', color='r')
plt.xticks(xticks,xlabels)

# Table title, etc
plt.title('Historical PM2.5')
plt.xlabel('1/1 of each year')
plt.ylabel('Average Islandwide PM2.5 level')
plt.show()

According to the graphs: There was a spike in PM2.5 and PSI levels during 2015 and late 2019, corresponding to smog incidents in SEA that eventually got blown by the wind into Singapore. Other than that, the levels remain mostly constant, hovering within a safe range. Historical Rainfall and Wet Bulb temperatures in Singapore have remained roughly consistent accross the years. Mean temperatures in Singapore have been on the rise since the beginning of the records (1982) and have never stopped since, with a total rough increase of about 1C Mean Minimum temperatures in Singapore have followed a similar trend with a noticeable jump after 2012. Mean Max temperatures have increased slightly over the years but mostly remain consistent. Mean humidity levels also experienced a substantial drop after 2012 and started fluctuating hard, though with a marked decrease overall. Next is plotting the recording data against each other according to timestamp to see if there are any possible relations between them. Graphs with no observable relationships will not be commented on.

# Plotting Humidity/Temperature Trend
# Extract timestamps and extra variables
timestamps1 = data3['timestamp']
extra_vars1 = data3['mean_rh']
timestamps2 = data4['timestamp']
extra_vars2 = data4['mean_temp']

# Find the common timestamps
common_timestamps, indices1, indices2 = np.intersect1d(timestamps1, timestamps2, return_indices=True)

# Use the indices to extract the corresponding extra variables
aligned_vars1 = extra_vars1[indices1]
aligned_vars2 = extra_vars2[indices2]

# Combine the common timestamps and the aligned extra variables into a structured array
humidity_temp = np.array(list(zip(common_timestamps, aligned_vars1, aligned_vars2)),
                  dtype=[('timestamp', 'i8'), ('mean_rh', 'f8'), ('mean_temp', 'f8')])

# Perform linear regression using numpy
A = np.vstack([humidity_temp['mean_rh'], np.ones(len(humidity_temp['mean_rh']))]).T
slope, intercept = np.linalg.lstsq(A, humidity_temp['mean_temp'], rcond=None)[0]
mean_trend_line = slope * humidity_temp['mean_rh'] + intercept

# Plot table 
plt.figure(figsize=(16,16))
plt.plot(humidity_temp['mean_rh'], mean_trend_line, color='red', label='Monthly Mean Trend Line')
plt.scatter(humidity_temp['mean_rh'],humidity_temp['mean_temp'], label='Monthly Mean')
# Table title, etc
plt.title('Humidity/Temperature Trend Chart')
plt.xlabel('Mean Humidity Level')
plt.ylabel('Mean Temperature Level')

# Humidity and Mean Temperature over Time
# Create the plot

We can see that out of the 3 charts, Minimum and Maximum Temperature seem to best indicate changes in humidity. However, all 3 charts share the same higher temperature levels compared to the line for humidity in the 2000-2012 time period, with the Maximum Temperature line following the shape of it most closely, implying that the higher humidity levels then were unaffected by higher than usual Mean and Minimum Temperatures. However, past the 2012 time period, the Maximum temperature line no longer follows the humidity line and drops below it instead, implying that the drop in humidity after 2012 is due to higher Mean and Minimum Temperatures. This raises the question as to what happened after the 2012 time period for the humidity levels to suddenly be affected by higher than useal Mean and Minimum Temperatures and why they were unaffected before.

# Pie chart of WBT 

# Round Wet Bulb Temperatures to the nearest integer
rounded_wbt_temp = np.round(data5['wbt_temp']).astype(int)

# Count the occurrences of each unique temperature
unique_temps, counts = np.unique(rounded_wbt_temp, return_counts=True)

# Define the main temps and initialize the dictionary to count occurrences of main and other temps
main_temps = [23, 24, 25, 26, 27]
temp_counts = {23:0,24:0,25:0,26:0,27:0,'Others':0}

# Categorize the temperatures
for temp, count in zip(unique_temps, counts):
    if temp in main_temps:
        temp_counts[temp] += count
    else:
        temp_counts['Others'] += count

# Plotting the data as a pie chart
plt.pie(temp_counts.values(), labels=temp_counts.keys(), autopct='%1.1f%%')
plt.title('Most Common Wet Bulb Temperatures (Rounded)')
plt.show()
print('Total Number of Variables: ' + str(len(rounded_wbt_temp)))

Total Number of Variables: 370344

As we can see from the pie chart, the most common temperatures are 26,25 followed by 24 degrees celcius (rounded). 23C has a 3.7% chance of occuring and 27C has a 8% chance. Anything higher or lower is an outlier with a 1.8% chance of occuring. This is derived from a total of 370344 records of data.

As a conclusion, Singapore is rapidly becoming a drier and warmer country as time progresses. Rainfall levels are also seeing more variance in recent years. It is recommended to prepare for such eventualities in the future. Luckily WBT levels as well as air pollution levels typically remain constant and within a safe range, though we should still prepare for any anomalies.

For those curious why there is a sudden drop in humidity after 2012:

With increase in temperature, the amount of water vapour in the air is expected to increase. This is because of the Clausius-Clapeyron (CC) equation, which suggests that the air can generally hold around 7% more water vapour for every 1 oC increase in air temperature. Therefore, under global warming, for the relative humidity to be constant the water vapour content in the air should increase at the same rate i.e. 7% increase for every 1oC increase in air temperature.

However, Singapore’s observation records show a decreasing trend in relative humidity. The reasons for this are: (1) large part of water vapour in the air over land comes from the seas surrounding Singapore, and (2) the land surface has been warming at a faster rate than the surrounding seas. Hence, the moisture from the surrounding seas is not enough to increase the water vapour over land at the CC rate, leading to a decreasing trend in RH.

src: https://www.mss-int.sg/docs/default-source/v3_reports/v3-sr-chap-05.pdf

Unfortunately there are no records of sea surface temperature in beta.data.gov.
